<br>
I nearly lost my broadband ISP when my Linux server requested a DNS update from a random machine in America, when the request was denied it kept resending requests (poor configuration on my part basically), the random machine I was requesting from complained to my ISP stating something like:<br>
<br>
As far as we can see this is an innocent and random error, however the sensitivity of the servers in question meens that we must maintain absolutely strict security protocol.<br>
<br>
There's two lessons in this, firstly going to his ISP (particularly his work ISP) might be more sucessfull and secondly that bad configuration of a Linux IP Masquerading server may result in accidental spamming of US Government servers with innocent DNS requests.<br>
